# Teach the Fleet to Schedule

## Question

Standing call (Joel, 2026-07-14): "the entire FLEET should know how to
schedule jobs wake panes etc. if i say 'schedule this' or whatever it
should be understood and executed." The capability exists (`joelclaw
wake at|in|list|cancel`, verbs WAKE/SPAWN/REVIVE); this question
distributes the KNOWLEDGE so any claude/pi/codex session on any machine
resolves "schedule this," "remind me at 6," "revive that loop tomorrow"
into the right `joelclaw wake` invocation without being told how.
Vehicle: dark-wizard ‚Äî a `pane-scheduling` skill (skills/ sync) with the
verb semantics, natural-language‚Üíflag mapping, and worked examples, plus
a thin fleet-graft block pointing at it from the standing prompts (the
machine-identity pattern). Includes what an agent does when the bus is
unreachable from its machine (honest failure line, never silent). Done
when the skill + graft are staged, installed on flagg, and a cold agent
session given "schedule a pane for 6pm to check X" produces the correct
command.

## Answer (2026-07-14)

Authored `dark-wizard/skills/pane-scheduling/SKILL.md` and the thin,
auto-discovered `scripts/fleet/pane-scheduling.block.md`. The skill teaches
the charter vocabulary (WAKE / SPAWN / REVIVE, due signal, late fire), real
flag contracts, loop-id lookup, list/cancel, and honest failure. The requested
bare `at 18:00` example was not copied because the real CLI rejects it; the
skill resolves natural language to an explicit local date plus time instead.

Natural-language map:

| Joel says | Verb | Required flag | Command shape |
|---|---|---|---|
| ‚ÄúWake the observer in 2h with X‚Äù | WAKE | `--target` | `joelclaw wake in 2h --verb wake --target observer --prompt 'X'` |
| ‚ÄúRemind me at 6pm to check X‚Äù | SPAWN | `--brief` | `joelclaw wake at '2026-07-15 18:00' --verb spawn --brief /absolute/path/check-x.svx` |
| ‚ÄúRevive that video loop tomorrow at 9am‚Äù | REVIVE | `--loop` | `joelclaw wake at '2026-07-16 09:00' --verb revive --loop <loop-id>` |

